T1  - Infant industry protection in the steel rail industry
AU  - Head, Keith
JO  - Journal of International Economics
VL  - 37
IS  - 3
SP  - 141
EP  - 165
PY  - 1994
DA  - 1994/11/01/
SN  - 0022-1996
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0022-1996(94)90043-4
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0022199694900434
KW  - Infant industry
KW  - Protection
KW  - Learning-by-doing
AB  - This paper examines a particular instance of infant industry protection: the case of the U.S. steel rail industry. It analyzes the joint roles of learning-by-doing, changing resource endowments, and tariff protection in the emergence of this industry. Making use of estimated demand and cost parameters, the paper simulates what would have happened to prices, production, and welfare under free trade. I calculate that, despite strong learning effects, the steel rail tariff hurt rail users in both the short and long runs. The tariff's overall effect on welfare was positive but fairly small.
